=== 12.3 The Chain Rule

Backpropagation is the chain rule from calculus, applied to a computation graph.

Suppose the loss depends on weight stem:[w] through a chain of intermediate values:

[stem]
++++
w \xrightarrow{f} z \xrightarrow{g} \mathcal{L}
++++

The chain rule says:

[stem]
++++
\frac{d\mathcal{L}}{dw} = \frac{d\mathcal{L}}{dz} \cdot \frac{dz}{dw}
++++

*If we know how stem:[\mathcal{L}] varies with stem:[z], and how stem:[z] varies with stem:[w], we multiply to get how stem:[\mathcal{L}] varies with stem:[w].*

In a transformer, the chain has hundreds of layers.
Backprop starts at the loss and works backward, multiplying local derivatives as it goes.
Each layer only needs two things: the gradient arriving from the layer above (called stem:[\delta], "delta"), and its own local derivative.

==== Step 1: A gradient update for one weight

[source,scheme]
----
; Move weight one step downhill along gradient.
(define (sgd-update-scalar weight gradient learning-rate)
  (- weight (* learning-rate gradient)))
----

If the gradient is positive (loss rises when stem:[w] increases), we subtract — decreasing stem:[w].
If negative, we add.
The learning rate stem:[\eta] scales how large the step is.

This is the entire idea.
Everything that follows is this rule, applied to millions of weights simultaneously.

=== 12.5 Backprop Through Softmax and Cross-Entropy

Chapter 9 stated the softmax-CE gradient without proof:

[stem]
++++
\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial z_j} = P(j) - \mathbb{1}[j = t]
++++

where stem:[z_j] are the logits and stem:[t] is the true token.

For the true token stem:[j = t]: gradient is stem:[P_t - 1] (negative, so we push stem:[z_t] up).
For every other token: gradient is stem:[P_j] (positive, so we push those logits down).
The model is nudged to be more confident about the correct answer.

[source,scheme]
----
; Gradient of cross-entropy loss w.r.t. logits.
(define (softmax-ce-backward logits true-id)
  (let* ((probs (softmax logits))
         (grad  (vector-copy probs)))
    (vector-set! grad true-id (- (vector-ref grad true-id) 1.0))
    grad))
----
